Research based on this conceptualization of parenting styles has produced a relatively consistent picture of the superiority of the authoritative style in inducing successful socialization and adjustment of children in Western culture (Baumrind, 1989; 
Chao, 2001;
Park & Bauer, 2002). Conversely, authoritarian and permissive parenting styles are considered to be linked with poorer child outcomes (Baumrind, 1989; 
Chao, 2001; Park & Bauer, 2002). Authoritarian styles have been associated with intimate relationship problems (Sharabany, Eshel, & Hakim, 2008), depression, low self-esteem, and difficulties in decision-making through to adulthood (Wenar & Kerig, 2000). Permissive styles have been associated with poor social skills and low self-esteem (Baumrind, 1991), irresponsibility, lack of empathy, and antisocial behavior (Wenar & Kerig, 2000). However, this evidence is far from conclusive.

The parenting style measure used was the Parenting Styles and Dimensions Questionnaire (PSDQ; 
Robinson, Mandleco, Frost Olsen, & Hart, 2001) that was designed to tap into theoretically meaningful parenting dimensions that are associated with child behavioral outcomes (Hart, Newell, & Olsen, 2003). The PSDQ, originally called the Parenting Practices Questionnaire (PPQ;
 Robinson, Mandleco, Olsen, & Hart, 1995), is a 62-item measure of self- and spouse-reported parenting practices for parents of preadolescent children. Items use a 5-point Likert scale (1 = never; 5 = always). The PSDQ was designed and confirmed by factor analysis to tap three styles of parenting based on 
Baumrind’s (1991) well-known typology—authoritative, authoritarian, and permissive. The measure yields a separate score for each dimension of parenting with larger numbers indicating increased use of parenting practices associated with a particular style. The authoritative scale (27 items) includes subscales for warmth and involvement (11 items), reasoning/induction (7 items), democratic participation (5 items), and good natured/easy going (4 items). The authoritarian scale (20 items) yields subscales for verbal hostility (4 items), corporal punishment (6 items), nonreasoning/punitive strategies (6 items), and directiveness (4 items). The permissive scale (15 items) yields subscales for lack of follow-through (6 items), ignoring misbehavior (4 items), and self-confidence (5 items). The PSDQ has been commended in a review of instruments assessing parenting practices (
Locke & Prinz, 2002) as one of the few instruments available for measurement of parental nurturance and discipline with psychometrically defensible scales. The measure has been adapted for effective use in multiple cultural settings including Russia (Hart, Nelson, Robinson, Olsen, & McNeilly-Choque, 1998), China (Wu et al, 2002), and African American Head Start communities (Coolahan, McWayne, Fantuzzo, & Grim, 2002). The scale has demonstrated good internal consistency reliability for mothers’ and fathers’ reports averaged together, for the authoritative subscale α = .91, for the authoritarian subscale α = .86, and for the permissive subscale α = .75 (Robinson et al, 1995). Internal consistency did not differ substantially across the parent who was the target of the report. In the present study, Cronbach’s alpha coefficients for the authoritative subscale were .85 and .84, for the authoritarian subscale .84 and .81, for the permissive subscale .79, and .81 for mothers and fathers respectively.

The Brief Symptom Inventory (BSI;
Derogatis & Spencer, 1982) is the abbreviated version of the Symptom Checklist-90—Revised (SCL-90-R), comprising 53 self-report symptoms rated on a 0 (not at all) to 4 (very much) scale. This measure provides distress indices and assessment of symptom load across 10 dimensions. In this study, the Global Severity Index (GSI) was used as a measure of general psychological distress, in line with recommendations by 
Derogatis and Spencer (1982) that this is the best single summary measure provided by the scale.
